definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To act or move in an awkward or confused manner ( often clumsily , incompetently , or carelessly ) . [from 1530s]
examples: Spiders build webs and wait for insects to bumble into them.

definitions.definition: ( originally Scotland and Northern England , transitive ) To carry out (a task) clumsily , incompetently , or with many careless mistakes; to bungle , to botch . [from ca. 1719?]

main_definition: ( intransitive ) To act or move in an awkward or confused manner ( often clumsily , incompetently , or carelessly ) . [from 1530s]
secondary_definitions: ( originally Scotland and Northern England , transitive ) To carry out (a task) clumsily , incompetently , or with many careless mistakes; to bungle , to botch . [from ca. 1719?]

definitions.definition: To boom , as a Eurasian bittern .
To speak in a rambling , incoherent , or indistinct manner, especially at tedious length.

main_definition: ( intransitive ) To boom , as a Eurasian bittern . [from ca. 1405]
secondary_definitions: ( intransitive , of an insect ) To buzz or bum . [from 1689]
( intransitive , frequently with on ) To speak in a rambling , incoherent , or indistinct manner, especially at tedious length. [from 1911]
( transitive , obsolete ) To grumble at; to blame . [1675–1781]
